        "heading": "Clinical Note",
        "section_value": "Chief Complaint\nRight shoulder pain following a football injury.\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports a history of playing football in the past and sustaining a tackle that resulted in shoulder pain. He describes the current pain as worsening over the past four days, particularly with reaching and lifting. He reports some difficulty lifting a box, but denies any numbness or tingling in his fingers. He has taken Tylenol, but it hasn't provided significant relief. He denies any fever or chills. He reports a minor head injury during the tackle.\nFindings\nPhysical exam reveals tenderness to palpation at the acromioclavicular joint. Range of motion is decreased, with pain on abduction and pronation. Vital signs are normal: blood pressure 122/76 mmHg, heart rate 82 bpm, oxygen saturation 95% on room air. The cervical spine exam is unremarkable. The nurse reports the right shoulder x-ray showed an acute acromioclavicular joint fracture.\nAssessment\nAcute acromioclavicular joint fracture of the right shoulder.\nPlan\nI am placing the patient in a sling for comfort. I am prescribing meloxicam 15 mg daily. I am ordering a cat scan of the right shoulder to assess the fracture further. I am referring the patient to physical therapy to strengthen the shoulder and avoid surgery. Follow up in four weeks if symptoms persist.",
